Patch Set 20: Code-Review-1

(9 comments)

This is pretty tricky.  I tend to think that the design could be simplified though.  I am having trouble with having features under policy-management, but not being packaged individually or operated individually.   Another issue I have is the base core functionality being handled by services is a little obscured.   I tend to think the SimpleLocking feature does not need to be a feature, and then avoid some of the issues I have.    This is a proposal, we should probably and discuss at length, I think though it would simplify it:

/* PolicyEngineManager - the code is simply to create a new method createLockManager 
 * with hooks in PolicyEngineFeatureApi to intercept the before and after for this new method
 * DistributedLocking and ServerPooling will intercept and will provide a PolicyResourceLockManager
 * object to handle all system locks onwards that override the "SimpleLockManager" default implementation.
 */

PolicyEngine:
     @Getter
   + PolicyResourceLockManager lockManager;
   + configure(Properties) {
       ...
       createLockManager(properties) 
       ...
     }
   + createLockManager(properties) {
       loop engineFeatures {
          PolicyResourceLockManager manager = engineFeatures.beforeCreateLockManager(engine, properties);
          if (manager != null) { this.lockManager = manager; return ..}
       }
       this.lockManager = new SimpleLockManager();
       engineFeatures.afterCreateLockManager(engine, this.lockManager, properties);
     }

     /* As a replacement for other feature hooks, the engine will forward 
      * PolicyResourceLockManager implementation as it is done for others*/

   + start/stop/shutdown/...() {
     ..
     lockManager.start/stop/shutdown()
     }

-------
/* PolicyResourceManager will extend Startable/.. as needed to be aware of Engine lifecycle */

PolicyResourceManager extends Startable, .. /* just for generality */ {
  + createLock(<lock-parameters>)
  + ... any others ..
}
-------

/* All the implementations now DistributedLock and ServerPool, etc .. will 
 * intercept the new hook:   PolicyEngineFeatureApi.beforeCreateLockManager(..)
 * they will return the DistributedLockManager or ServerPoolLockManager */

/* From that point on the LockManager can be accessed on a singleton fashion 
 * from the PolicyEngine: PolicyEngine.getManager().getResourceLockManager();
 * alternatively, the feature could cache it (I don't think there's a need
 * to make it a singleton */

/* So the implementations with override the createLock(..) and will do all
 * their magic within their feature realm
 */
ie.


SimpleLockManager implements PolicyResourceManager {
   /* this is not a feature */
   /* this would pretty much the content of "SimpleLockingFeature" with the audit */
   createLock(..) { /* is pretty much the content of SimpleLockingFeature.beforeCreateLock */ }
}

DistributedLockManager implements PolicyResourceManager {
   /* this would pretty much the content of "SimpleLockingFeature" with the audit */
   createLock(..) { /* .. */ }
}

ServerPoolLockManager implements PolicyResourceManager {
   /* this would pretty much the content of "SimpleLockingFeature" with the audit */
   createLock(..) { /* .. */ }
}

/* There are no changes in the Lock interface and derived classes */
